# MCP Error Handling

## API-Based MCP Tools (BlazeMeter, Datadog, Confluence)

- Allow 5 seconds between each MCP tool call to prevent `Too Many Requests` API error (HTTP 429)
- Retry up to 3 times on transient failures (network errors, timeouts, 5xx responses)
- Wait briefly between retries
- After 3 failed retries, stop and report the error to the user
- Allow 5-10 seconds before API retry to prevent `Too Many Requests` API error (HTTP 429)

## Code-Based MCP Tools (PerfAnalysis, PerfReport, JMeter)

- Do NOT retry on failure
- Report the error immediately with:
  - The full error message
  - Missing file paths (if applicable)
  - Expected vs actual structure (if applicable)
- Ask the user for next steps

## Never Modify MCP Source Code

- Never attempt to fix MCP tool code or modify source files to work around errors
- The MCP tools are external dependencies — treat them as read-only
- If a tool produces unexpected output, report it to the user

## Stop on Unrecoverable Failures

- Stop the workflow and report to the user on any unrecoverable failure
- Do not proceed to the next workflow step if the current one fails
- Provide enough context for the user to diagnose the issue

## Error Reporting Format

When reporting errors, include:
- Which MCP tool failed
- The full error message or status
- What step in the workflow failed
- What was expected vs what happened
- Suggested next steps (if obvious)
